<Date>1544034411145</Date><rating>5<//rating><Review>I used their website to rent a storage unit. It was very simple. I received email confirmations as well as a call from the manager to set up a time to see the unit and facility. It is clean and quiet.
You dont need to open the gate to enter the facility during office business hours. However for sake of security I wish that wasnt the case. Other places I have rented at, no matter what, you could not enter unless you had an activation code. There is one person in the office, so having the gate open all day makes me feel less secure, regardless of the fact that you need to use the code to get into the buildings.
There is no elevator, only a lift. It's not complicated to use. However, if you are unfortunate enough to need to use it after some discourteous person who leaves it on the second floor and doesnt close the door to the lift so it can operate, you have to go up the stairs yourself to send the lift down. It would have been nice if they had an elevator, after moving boxes and such, you kinda dont want to climb up stairs too. But no matter what you will have to, if you are on the second floor, as people are not allowed on the lift.
The facility is clean with plywood for floors. It seemed strange to me actually. Gave the place a less permanent, incomplete feel.

<Review>(A big thank you to our friendly server, Kelsey!) Hands down the very best cafe I've ever visited! The prices are more than fair for the amount of food you're getting, and the quality! I got the breakfast burrito with sausage and it's definitely become my favorite breakfast burrito to date. The golden hashbrowns, eggs, melted cheese, and sausage were all incredible, especially paired with their fresh orange juice, topped with an orange slice. ‚ô° I also had a craving for their french toast and asked if I could have that as my side, instead of the toast and bagel they offer. They said I could, and I'm so glad they did because their french toast was so good--it was a close second to my mom's homemade french toast slices! Not too sweet, not overloaded with powdered sugar, just perfect. And our server, Kelsey, was so polite, kind, and friendly, definitely made us feel welcomed and attended to despite us sitting outside. I've found in many restaurants, if you ask for outdoor seating, the servers tend to forget about you. But here, not one, not two, but three! servers visited our tables to check up on us and deliver our food and drinks. My girlfriend got the Coconut Cream Iced Coffee paired with the Berry Toast that was loaded with blueberries, strawberries, a delicious spread of cream cheese and syrup, I even asked for a bite. Her coffee was amazing, too, and came in a huge, super cute mason jar! If you're ever in long beach and you want quality breakfast for a great price, make sure to stop by Meant to Be Cafe!<//Review>< rating>
5</rating>

<Review>Stopped by with my lovely wife last Saturday during the "soft opening".  Not everything was available but a lot more was available than I would expect from a soft opening. All in all the food tasted great and the service was next level! They have a clothing shop attached to the caf√© that has a bunch of stylish ladies clothing too.
Anyway I'm giving it 5 stars because the food tasted good, the service was great and most importantly for me the location is as good as it gets for local neighborhood people. I have no association with the owners or this business other than paying money for food. That said I want nothing more than for this business to thrive in my neighborhood, if you are in the area or live in this neighborhood give Meant to be Cafe a shot, I think this family owned and operated business will make you happy that you did.<//Review>< Pics>

< review>
I recently walked into a bright pleasant windowed room, walls hung with affirmations and mandalas. This was my first time at "Meant To Be Cafe", and I was greeted with a smile and treated to first rate service.  My friend was all smiles, eating the breakfast sandwich with organic cage free eggs, perfectly sunny side up with tasty homemade tater tots. The best coffee I've had, since my trip in Italy, two years ago. I drink it black. Yum!  However, my friend drank his coffee with cream.  He liked the old school cream pitcher and the sweetner option of granulated honey. I ordered a vegan pita sandwich with hummus, cucumbers, tomatoes, bean sprouts and red onion (optional). Dipping in salsa added a scrumtious kick to my meal. The menu is an eclectic variety with brunchy comfort foods, and vegan options. Next time, I'm ordering the french toast recommend by my talented friend Brandi who plays there once a week at their open mic.< /review>

The store is really cool. It's full of beautiful crystals and cool items. I love being positive and hate negative reviews. But the way I was treated was not right ......

I'm giving this store a one star rating because I was treated UNFAIRLY.
The minute I walked in the store this women who works there wanted to argue with me.
She has dark hair. She has a cold personality. I went into the store to look at the crystals and necklaces.

I needed to wash my hands first. So as my husband and I went into the moonstone store, I asked immediately if they had a bathroom to wash my hands. I happened to touch a piece of clothing from another store that had a stain on it. I got really grossed out.
The lady said no. But she said that there is a bathroom next door. So I ended up going across the street to wash my hands.

After I washed my hands, my husband and I went back into the moonstone store. The lady looked at me and said in a demanding voice. You must sanitize your hands or ware gloves. I looked at her and said, don't you remember me.
I'm the one that came in to this store and asked if she has a restroom to wash my hands.

I showed her my hands. I told her that I already washed them. I showed her my hands two times. My hands were wet and had soap on them still. I told her that I can't use hand sanitizer because I get eczema. I get really dry cracked hands that bleed from using sanitizer.

She looked at me and said argumentatively, don't you know that we're in the middle of a pandemic. The government will shut us down. I was wearing a face mask. She said that this is serious. She said that she was not there to see me wash my hands.

She told me that I have to use the hand sanitizer or wear gloves.
I put on gloves. I tried to look around in the store but I felt intimidated and attacked. She was so confrontational. I told her that it is bad customer service to treat a customer this way.The lady did not leave me alone in the store.
I asked her to give me space because she was making me feel very uncomfortable and nervous. I told her that she was making me feel uncomfortable. She just stared at me. She said that she is 5 feet away from me.

<Text>Getting my first jab of Moderna's vaccine at AFC Urgent Care in Fresno CA was quite a breeze (easy, i.e.).  I searched for a place where vaccination is currently being done through the Fresno County web page and found AFC UC, which was near my home and served by a FAX bus service.  I reserved an open slot and got the first jab ALL on the same day, April 2.  The online application process was quite convenient, easy to do using my smartphone.  It only took about 10-15 minutes waiting time in a lobby area with plenty of seats, lots of good outdoor lighting through glass windows, quite roomy and very tidy.  The person who gave the shot was quite efficient and I barely felt the jab.  Afterwards, I stayed at the lobby for about 20 minutes, as advised by the staff.  So far, 2 days later, the slight soreness on my left arm is gone and thankfully no complications, so far, whatsoever.  I highly recommend AFC Urgent Care.  Thank you very much, and I'm looking forward to my second vaccine jab.<//Text>< UserId.>

< Review>
Built at the sight of a converted theatre, Jardines De San Juan is the sister restaurant to Manuel‚Äòs in Aptos. Jardines is sprawled out over a huge patio garden with an outbuilding doubling as a bar and the original main theatre building as the (limited) indoor seating. But this restaurant is designed for outdoor seating and with the beautiful weather of the region it‚Äôs perfect for that. The food is good, and I recommend the cheese enchiladas which are made with Jack cheese and onions which is a flavourful and slightly different spin than your typical recipe. They alsoo have delicious chilli rellenos, and my favourite is their Friday night special which is red snapper served on a bed of rice with a sort of rancheros sauce on top and it‚Äôs to die for!<//Review>

Going to Jardines for almost 30 years. The ambiance and food can't be beat! Worth the drive from the Bay Area!< /Text>
<name>Dan Dalal<//name></record></dataset><record>
<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNxfceqMrdJlrNq1XC40YJjQ5IjOZu9q7-Hn-Um=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNEUgN3cgWBFgBaGRXtMl_NEUVKCHbYcLe6dNTf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics>< Text>
We were apart of a very large preplanned dinner party...about 20+.  Despite being sat outside in 50ish degrees with solid winds were told the servers were only allowed to place 2 propane heaters outside for our group.  Bummer.  Jardines didn't have throw blankets for guests either.  Other restaurants of a similar caliber provide these for cold days / nights.  Jardines needs to step up.  The food was mediocre.  I give 4 stars because the servers really saved the day presetting tables prior to our visit, taking orders quickly, answering questions, and yet being able to check on everyone once in a while.  The prices are far too high for what Jardines delivers.  The patio must be really nice on a warm day and is beautiful in appearance so I suspect the higher food prices are justified by the environment.</Text>

< Review>
Great courtyard experience. Really good Mexican food. I had the People's Choice Burrito. Nice relaxing atmosphere for family dining. We enjoyed the courtyard with umbrellas but they also offer indoor seating. In back of the courtyard is a larger open area, filled with mature succulents and other plant life. This might be a good location for catered parties and other events.

People's Choice Burrito:

Winner of the 2015, 2016 & 2017 People's Choice Award at the Watsonville Burrito Bash! Crispy carnitas, jack cheese, whole beans, sour cream, pico de gallo, cilantro, onions, and red salsa.<//Review>

<user>103871958027851665426<//user><user_name>Marc Kleinmaier< /user_name><Time>1561844519413</Time>< rate>
5< /rate>
< review>
Such a great outdoor patio! Set amidst a beautiful and quaint outdoor garden, this restaurant offers a classic Mexican menu, friendly service and delicious food. Whenever we visit San Juan Bautista, we always make sure to have lunch here. The building seems like an old world, authentic hacienda and is reminiscent of classic Mexican architecture and Old Town San Diego. They serve a spicy picante sauce with the chips but also have a great pico de Gallo, which they'll happily bring when asked. Don't miss this place; it's memorable!</review>

< Review>
My husband and I drove to San Juan Bautista to celebrate Valentine‚Äôs Day because of the beautiful mission and the seemed attractive restaurant Jardines de San Juan.  The meal was a total disappointment!  The services were very good but the food was sloppy.  I ordered carne asada, the skirt steak was so salty!  They just laid the meat on a huge bed of rice and refried beans; there was nothing elegant about the dish.  My husband ordered the snapper special, it was heavily breaded and also laid on a huge bed of rice.  You just felt that they just speedily put some food together without any desire to make the food special.  It is a place for quantity but not for quality.  I will not be going back there again.< /Review>

<rate>5<//rate>< review>
Jardines de San Juan is just a couple of blocks from the mission and is a wonderful way to wrap up a visit to the beautiful mission. The food is delicious, the ambience lovely, and the staff are friendly. Do sit outside under the colorful umbrellas, if you are there when the weather is good. Everything is delicious here, the basic chile rellenos and the tamales are delicious. Try the seafood enchilada without fail. The albondigas are hearty and perfect for cool weather or at the end of a hard day.</review>

First, the waitress, Edelmira, never brought us water or offered but that may have been a simple mishap.  I ordered a lemondrop martini. It barely had any sugar at all around the rim and I asked for a bit more. The waitress said to me "YOU ASKED for a lemon drop, that's a lemon drop." I asked for more sugar around the rim again. She took the drink and in 5 seconds returned the exact drink untouched and unaltered. It was obvious because the space where I'd taken a sip remained on the glass around the rim. Before I could say anything, she left the table and my fiance noticed her actually roll her eyes.
Naturally, I asked to speak to the manager on duty, not for free food or to complain needlessly but because Edelmira was incredibly rude and simply would not properly wait on our table.
I explained the situation, Gabe kindly and simply brought another drink as well as returned that one as I had not taken but a sip. Gabe is the only reason this restaurant gets a star period in my book. The waitress returned with the check but did not offer any further service.<//text><pics>None<//pics><Resp>None<//Resp><gmap_id>0x8091f8d53c1d687f:0xd2a9083fc0f82fb7<//gmap_id></record>

< text>
Came in tonight @6:50pm . with family of 14 (5 of them being kids) to celebrate a bday. 1 guy & 1 girl working as Hostess. I was told 20-25min wait time by the kid for outside seating. It was nice weather and we thought -okay cool this will be a fantastic evening. We are not from the area. we were told about this place so thats how we ended here. .. 50min later the kid tells me he's been waiting on two customers to leave in order to clear the table he needs to set up 3 tables for us. Clearly he can see the kids that are with us. That wasn't the only table . There where plenty more tables  that he could have  moved around . it's not Rocket Science. its Tetris. him and the girl kept taking in parties of 2's and 3's that came in way after us , instead of making some minor adjustments with the tables, and they were not on the same page at all. 1hour Later we sat down . we weren't served any waters. 10min later we went to ask for a waiter to take our order. If not who knows how long we would have waited. By the time we got served our food it was 8:30pm , and sure enough (what i had told my family ) came true. They messed up so Bad. Unbelievable!  They brought 3 kid's enchilada plates when we had ordered 3 kid's Quesadilla plates. Some one had asked for no onions and sure enough they got onions. What if he was Allergic to it? Hmm.. We asked for a glass to pour a bottled beer in (when we ordered drinks) and they couldnt even do that right LOL. SMH. Kid's had to wait an extra 10min on top of almost 2hours  to eat. By this time it was almost 9pm , it wasnt light outside anymore and it got cold outside.
Someone talked to the manager and the discount he gave was 20% off the total (which i later was told about after we had left) . like what is 20% gonna do??? They Messed up so badly. I mean Seriously management!? What a Joke!
I have Never had such a HORRIBLE experience like this before EVER. I have worked in restaurants before , and know exactly what it is to do Everything in my power to take care of the customer effectively and efficiently, ESPECIALLY if they have kids. But this place , starting with the hostess , dont care and aren't trained well enough.  i will let my friend  (who suggested this place) and everyone i know know that this place is Garbage.
Never will return , not even if they offer a free meal. This establishment can't handle big groups.
Avoid this place . spend the money somewhere else . Ain't worth it.< /text>

< Review>
We arrived mid-afternoon, just after 3 pm, on a Friday. It was 81 degrees in the shade. We sat in the back garden area and requested a full shade table, since one of our party was red headed and very fair skinned. By the end of our meal we had all squeezed together on one side of the table to avoid the sun.

Our meal was average for the items ordered. Chile rellanos, chicken enchilada, and grilled rock cod.

The service was subpar. Only two waters for three people. Had to ask for a third water after waiting and waiting. No water refills until we were able to stop someone to ask.

Come here if you have lots of time to sit and wait. Seemed to be plenty of wait staff just not ones working with our waiter.

The guacamole was outstanding!

In the future we will go back to our usual place for Mexican food with much better service.<//Review>

< review>
I've had their vegan burrito twice. The first time was made as described on the menu. The veggies were great and the burrito was enormous and very flavorful.

The second time I added cheese to my burrito. I know. Not actually vegan anymore but neither am I. The burrito has bell peppers, zucchini and other crispy veggies along with some seriously tasty salsa and whole beans.

My friend ordered a super carne asada burrito with everything. I watched him devour it. So it must have been delicious just like mine. Both times the food was ordered to go but their dining room looks welcoming and I'd like to dine in one of these days.< /review>

<Text>Ambiance: 4 or 5 stars
Food Quality: 3 stars
Service: mixed
Price: too high for what it is

I live in San Juan, and have eaten here many times. The location and gardens in the back are beyond beautiful. The food is decent, no complaints. The waiters are usually nice and often attentive, however I have seen full trays of food (like 6 plates) crash to the floor of the brick patio on several occasions (one time it happened twice in the same visit!). The prices are high, let's be clear, however they are still low enough for this to be a nice place to go for a special night out, like a birthday or anniversary, etc. The reason I am writing this review (and only giving 3 stars overall) is because of their senseless policies that they randomly trot out... yesterday (Mother's Day) was the last straw. I called to place an order to be picked up (I live about a quarter mile from the restaurant) and the guy on the phone informed me that due to the "Mother's Day rush" (it was 5:15 when I called) they would not be taking to go orders over the phone.
Excuse me? Oh, but they will do to go orders, if you want to show up and place the order in person and then stand around and wait while they cook it. This makes NO SENSE. Unless they think I am going to place an order and then not show up, this policy is pointless. What is the difference between telling you what I want in person, and telling you on the phone? It certainly doesn't alleviate the rush, if anything it just makes it more crowded in the waiting area. Also, it is Mother's Day, and I am not going to go stand outside their building for 30 minutes while they make the food for absolutely no reason while my wife is at home with the kids, so we just got something else for dinner. Which may have been their hope, since this (the losing of business) is the only way their policy alleviated the rush. If I am going to be paying $15 for a burrito and $7 for one taco (yes, that is the price), at least let me order from the comfort of my home.</Text><Date>1557779880022< /Date></record></dataset><record>

< text>
Over many years driving 101, have always stopped at this gem of a place in this classic jewel of an old western farm town. Superb tasty btkfst, lunch, dinner & charming service with a completely calming, deeply satisying ambience every time. The plain sunshades (top photo) were long replaced by a bright mix of blue, yellow, orange, & green shades creating, especially in sunlight, a marvelous  kaleidoscopic effect that rivals all the wonderful hanging geraniums for attention!  Have your tastebuds & cameras ready!< /text>

< Rate>
2</Rate>
< review>
driving back from sac town we did a search for "mexican restaurant" and was excited to see jardine de san juan with a high rating ... and when we got there it was busy and people were waiting... so we thought it must be great... but it wasn't.

we sat down and were served stale chips (they were sitting outside in a bin)... we ordered carne asada tacos with rice and refried beans... and waited 20 minutes for the order... meanwhile we ordered some drinks, a margarita with cazadores tequila and a sangria... both were lacking the proper amount of alcohol, they tasted like sugar syrup... when we got the food the plate was scalding hot from being under a heat lamp too long, the beans had melted cheese all throughout them, and the main course, the carne asada tacos, tasted like gristle meat (low quality).

so, all in all it was a 2 1/2 star experience and way overrated and overpriced --- spent about $60 here on food  and drinks that were subpar

if you like big portions of average mexican style food then eat here... if you want taste -- sabroso -- then go elsewhere

we won't be back< /review>

<time>1519060274600< /time><UserId.>112371663577599533951</UserId.><GmapID>0x8091f8d53c1d687f:0xd2a9083fc0f82fb7</GmapID><Pictures>None</Pictures></record></dataset><record>
< Text>
We ate here during their annual Dia de los Muertos night and that became an immediate mistake. The restaurant could not handle the amount of people that had shown up. The wait staff forgot about us a few time and we had to flag down other employees. Our food was lackluster and disproportional on portions. (For example, my enchiladas were these two dainty little objects on this enormous plate of rice and beans.) When we got our bill they had added on the drinks and appetizers from another table. When they brought it back corrected, it still had other people's stuff on it. On the third and final correction, it was finally correct. It was then that I discovered that they charged us for the guacamole that they brought us with our chips and salsa! Nobody told us there was a charge for it, nor did they ask us if we wanted it.

Next door they were sampling tequila, dancing and having a costume contest for Dia de los Muertos. The people were getting too drunk, too loud and they only provided a couple Porta-Potties for them on a dark unlit street.  The drunks and others had to come into the restaurant to use the restroom. Also, they were allowing Halloween costumes into their Dia de los Muertos costume contest. It was supposed to be for Catrin only, not Leather-face and Pokemon.

Maybe on a different day I would've had a different experience...?<//Text>

< user_name>
Neil Hunt< /user_name>
<Resp>None< /Resp><review>Once again this Tues after Labor Day '13 -while heading back to T.Oaks CA from S.F.I repeated a habit of many years & happily spun off the 101 between Gilroy & Salinas to head east 2 miles to this always marvelous to visit Natl/State protected Historic 'old town' (actually an incorporated city) It was not too hot with nice cooling breezes off the Monterey peninsula and as usual not packed with crowds of visitors! I headed straight down 3rd St with the prime purpose of enjoying yet another in a long line of always-delicious Mex-lunch in this highly attractive & spacious flowered-filled garden setting. Waited on by a warmly smiling 'Joe' I strolled about taking photos then settled to enjoy a really delicious tall mango-drink he'd recommended when I baulked at my longed-for cold Mex-beer-what with facing that long drive. The daily special of Baja-style Tilapia fish tacos with all those usual good fixins was his recommendation too & was perfect! They have never failed to satisfy this lunch-loving traveler at their always great & peaceful away-from-the-world retreat! You'll do very well to stop here & bring an appetite! Then do as I did-stroll the old historic district with your camera at hand!<//review><Date>1378333965227< /Date><gmap_id>0x8091f8d53c1d687f:0xd2a9083fc0f82fb7< /gmap_id><user_id>101075716115741438713<//user_id><rate>5< /rate>< Pictures>
